  "prompt": "Is Mexican food in Mexico much hotter (spicier) than the Mexican food served in the United States?",
  "response": "Mexican cuisine in Mexico tends to be more complex and varied in flavor compared to Mexican food in the United States. While there is some variation, the spiciness level can depend on the specific region and dish. Some key differences include:\n\n1. Mexican regional cuisines have more nuanced and diverse uses of chili peppers, often focusing on flavor complexity rather than just heat.\n\n2. In Mexico, dishes are more likely to use fresh chili peppers and a wider variety of chile types, which can create more balanced heat.\n\n3. Tex-Mex cuisine in the U.S. often emphasizes spiciness and tends to use fewer varieties of chili peppers.\n\n4. Some regions in Mexico, like the Yucatan Peninsula, have traditionally milder cuisines, while others, like Puebla, are known for spicier dishes.\n\n5. In Mexico, diners often have the option to add their own choice of salsa or hot sauce to adjust the heat level to their preference.\n\nSo while it's not accurate to say Mexican food in Mexico is always hotter, it is generally more diverse and nuanced in its use of chili peppers compared to typical Mexican-American restaurant fare.",
